24964027.review:
As always with SE, the writing was god-awful in a very special, unique way, but gameplay was solid, the challenge [i]was there[/i] and the world felt very immersive.

Pros:
- bona fide open-world Final Fantasy for real, you guys;
- unconventional in a lot of ways (e.g. Lightning acts as three characters in one with three seperate ATB gauges and stuff);
- quite a lot of things to do and quite some variety;
- Lightning is extremely customizable and open-ended;
- battles are actually challenging almost from the very beginning;
- most monsters being puzzles is nice;
- the cute integrated dress-up game is continuously entertaining;
- as you ride trains, visit cafes and stay at hotels, the world starts to feel actually immersive.

Cons:
- Square-Enix writing. I can't tell why in 99% of their games they keep doing this sh*t where characters stand in front of each other, robotically state their motivations (sometimes the same exact thing again and again five or six times in a row, often repeated in 3-4 following cutscenes almost freaking verbatim) and then get "developed" by suddenly changing motivations to the opposite out of the blue. And don't give me this "it's the Japanese style of storytelling" b*llsh*t, because it isn't "Japanese" storytelling, it's fanfic-grade storytelling.
- MMORPG-ey sh*t (dozens of bring N things quests etc.; but very few are mandatory, so its o.k.).

23242239.review:
A very good game with a very good port.  What's the issue with it?  It's drastically different from your other Final Fantasy titles.

Storyline;
The end of the Lightning Saga, wrapping up the Fabula Nova Crystallis universe. And man, what an ending! The storyline is kind of spread thin; the bulk of the storyline is on the Final Day. In order to unlock the Final Day, you need to gain Eradia, the bulk of which is gained from saving the souls of some familiar friends. It's a very hit-or-miss storyline; I can see how people might not like it, but for me, it's one of my most favorite stories of all time.

Gameplay;
This is where the drastic changes come in. While the previous FF13 games were more relatable to turn-based games, Lightning Returns is more relatable to action games.  Some fights require you to move around the field in order to strike a specific part of an enemy.

You have 3 "schemata" each with their own ATB gauges. Using actions require different amounts of ATB, with your other schemata's ATB gauges recharing while they aren't currently in use.  There are some action elements, like Perfect Guards and Perfect Attacks, where you perform guards/attacks on a specific frame in order to reduce damage to 0/increase damage.

Almost immediately from the start, the game becomes open-world.  While you spend the first 15-20 minutes or so in Luxerion, you're soon given free reign over the 4 different regions; enemies are all relative in strength for the first 7 days.  After the 7th day, they get modifiers to their HP, Attack, and Magic stats.

Difficulty;
It may just be because I'm terrible at action games, but even on normal mode, I found this to be the most challenging Final Fantasy game i've played.  One of the story bosses in The Wildlands means business, it took me an hour or two to find the right setup. 

The superbosses are an insane challenge.  Aeronite in particular - you've got to take off 8-9m health within 3 minutes.  The first few times I attempted him, I was barely able to take off 3m before he took off.  I ended up completely cheesing it with a whole lot of ethers.

Music;
I may not have been listening too closely, because I didn't catch much, if any, songs unique to Lightning Returns.  It uses a mix of music from FF13 and FF13-2.  Luckily only the good tracks from 13-2!

