20722012.review:
Pros:  
a) it is a decent conclusion to the FF XIII story.  All kinds of messed up but decent, nonetheless; 
b) the schemata system is decent;  
c) battles do require more attention than your typical turn-based system;
d) decent voice acting - special mention goes to the voice talent behint Chocolina, Mog and Lumina;

Cons:
a) throughout the entire game you'll fight the same twenty or so types of enemies.  Many borrowed from the previous two games with no changes or variations to the animations.   Considering one of the highlights of the game is the different battle system, it is vexing they did not introduce a larger variety of enemies to showcase its potential;
b) the storyline is borderline nonsensical with the forced injection of religious overtones.  A mash of plots of concepts that were probably leftover from the previous two games;
c) game starts off on the wrong foot with a weak hook;
d) in case you don't have enough stress in your life they made the game so that it requires players to manage their time, with a clock in your face for 90% of the game.  You will always feel rushed and end up sprinting for most of the game.  If you're looking for a relaxing RPG where you can take your time to explore your surroundings, this is not it.

After a hundred side-quests and a fair bit of grinding you will realize this is a story about gods and man.  About love and chaos.  About souls and crystals.  About despair and hope.  About death and salvation.  About self-fulfilling prophecies and human frailty.  About strength and self-image.
